na they deal with. The articles are divided into two main sections, those centering on the relations between the various forms of French used in Canada and France, and those concentrating on the various forms of French found in Canada and their contacts with other languages.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn French.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aFrench languagexDialectszCanadavCongresses. 0aFrench languagexDialectszFrancevCongresses. 0aFrench languagexVariationvCongresses. 0aFrench languagezCanadavCongresses. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh1 aBagola, Béatrice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeutler, Corinne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBougy, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoulanger, Jean-Claude, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrasseur, Patrice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCajolet-Laganière, Hélène, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChauveau, Jean-Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFaribault, Marthe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGauthier, Pierre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGendron, Jean-Denis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGolopentia, Sanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHalford, Peter W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoriot, Brigitte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLavoie, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLepelley, René, econtributor.4ctb4h